Package org.apache.logging.log4j.kit.logger

Class AbstractLogger

java.lang.Object
org.apache.logging.log4j.kit.logger.AbstractLogger
All Implemented Interfaces:
org.apache.logging.log4j.Logger, org.apache.logging.log4j.spi.ExtendedLogger
@NullMarked public abstract class AbstractLogger extends Object implements org.apache.logging.log4j.spi.ExtendedLogger
Base implementation of a Logger.

It is highly recommended that any Logger implementation extend this class.

Implementation details

Control flow

The typical control flow of a log message inside this class is:

  1. Methods from the Logger interface call location-aware methods.
  2. Location-aware methods (mostly in the ExtendedLogger interface) have a fqcn parameter to allow logging bridge developers to provide fully qualified class name of the logger entry point, used to determine the caller class and method when location information needs to be logged.
  3. Filters methods are evaluated to check if the message should be logged.
  4. If the user didn't supply a Message parameter, a message factory is called.
  5. The logMessageSafely(java.lang.String, java.lang.StackTraceElement, org.apache.logging.log4j.Level, org.apache.logging.log4j.Marker, org.apache.logging.log4j.message.Message, java.lang.Throwable) method is invoked, which handles recursion and exceptions.
  6. Control is passed to the abstract doLog(java.lang.String, java.lang.StackTraceElement, org.apache.logging.log4j.Level, org.apache.logging.log4j.Marker, org.apache.logging.log4j.message.Message, java.lang.Throwable) method.

Performance

Most methods in this class are tuned for performance. Specifically, try to keep the hot methods to 35 bytecodes or less: this is within the MaxInlineSize threshold on Java 7 and Java 8 Hotspot and makes these methods candidates for immediate inlining instead of waiting until they are designated "hot enough".
